expansion of model size, the ability of LLMs has a qualitative leap, and there is an ability that does not exist in small models but is generated in LLMs, called emergent capability (Zoph et al. 2022), such as in context learning (ICL), Chain of thought (CoT), etc. ICL enables LLMs to mimic existing examples to solve new problems by adding input–output samples to the prompts; CoT adds intermediate reasoning steps to the prompts. Therefore, the emergent capability in downstream task scenarios show strong application potential. CoT enables the model to show strong logical reasoning capability when dealing with complex problems (Wei et al. 2022). At the same time, this capability also provides an opportunity for attackers, who can use the complexity of the CoT to construct more elaborate and hidden adversarial samples. These samples can disrupt the model’s reasoning process and cause the model to make incorrect decisions at critical points. The transferability of adversarial examples further aggravates the severity of this issue (Li et al. 2024). Due to the similarity and interoperability between LLMs, attackers can transfer the adversarial examples generated on one model to another to achieve cross-model attacks. This is due to the need to consider the security of multiple models simultaneously. Applying LLMs in critical domains such as finance and healthcare is pivotal to the accuracy of decision-making. However, if the attacker can successfully use the adversarial samples to carry out a transfer-based attack to interfere with the decision-making process of these models, it may result in incalculable economic losses or security risks.For instance, when a medical large language model is subjected to adversarial attacks, it may provide incorrect recommendations in diagnostic systems, leading to erroneous or delayed treatments, which directly threaten patient health. Similarly, adversarial attacks on financial large language models can result in financial assistants offering inaccurate investment advice, causing users to incur economic losses and affecting the stability of financial markets. To address the above problems, this paper utilizes different perturbation levels of adversarial attacks on different General LLMs, and different types of tasks, targeting the key data parts in the prompt samples and combining the CoT to construct the adversarial transfer prompt samples against different General LLMs. Moreover, this paper comprehensively evaluates the performance differences of different LLMs when facing adversarial prompt samples by comparing them with baseline attack methods and discussing the effectiveness and universal applicability of CoT-based transfer adversarial attacks on LLMs. Eventually, based on the information about the attention distribution of the LLMs, we can further explore the reasons why the LLMs are misled under the
strong logical reasoning capability of CoT, and find the adversarial weakness of the CoT of the LLMs, to provide support for the enhancement of the robustness of the LLMs, and help to realize the LLMs’ active security. This paper will provide support for improving the robustness of LLMs and help realize LLMs’ active safety.Hence, the contributions of this paper are as follows.
• To maintain the structural similarity between the substitute model and the target model, this paper uses a pre-trained model based on Transformer and obtains the fine-tuning version of this model on different tasks as the substitute model. At the same time, the OpenAttack framework is used to get different perturbation levels. • In the process of constructing transfer adversarial samples, this article extracts the optimal task instructions in the PromptBench framework to ensure the initial performance of the LLMs. To effectively stimulate the CoT capability, the CoT technology is utilized to fuse the optimal CoT trigger and the LLMs reasoning process. • This study focuses on LLMs with varying performance and parameter scales as the target models. Single perturbation level and hybrid perturbation levels’ adversarial attacks are implemented, while DAC, ADAC, APDR, and ASR are used as evaluation indexes to demonstrate the validity and general applicability of CTTA. • CosSim, PPL, and GErr are used to assess the quality of CTTA-Prompt samples, and the Attention by Gradient technique visualizes the distribution of Attention to discuss the causes of the model’s erroneous responses and the advantages of incorporating the CoT technique for adversarial attacks.
Related work
Textual adversarial attacks
An adversarial attack deceives the victim model by adding perturbations to the original samples to cause the model to produce false outputs. An adversarial attack originated in the field of computer vision, and many classical adversarial attack algorithms have been proposed, such as C&W Attack, UAP, FGSM, GAN, etc (Carlini and Wagner 2017; Moosavi-Dezfooli et al. 2017; Zhang et al. 2023; Zhao et al. 2018). Due to the discreteness of text, the image adversarial attack algorithm cannot be directly used for text adversarial attacks. However, a series of adversarial attack algorithms are derived from the field of text adversarial attack. These attack algorithms are classified into character-level, word-level, sentence-level, and multi-level. Character-level attacks mainly perturb the


