characters in the original input, including the addition, deletion, replacement, and exchange of characters. DeepWordBug (Gao et al. 2018) algorithm uses the characterlevel modification algorithm to attack important words, and the TextBugger (Li et al. 2019) algorithm combines character-level and word-level attacks. It implements both black-box and white-box attacks. Word-level attacks mainly scramble the input text by word substitution and have a higher quality of adversarial samples compared to word-level attacks. The BERT-Attack (Li et al. 2020) algorithm performs word substitution based on the ordering of importance of words obtained from the masking of words. Compared with the same level text attack model TextFooler (Jin et al. 2020), BERT-Attack significantly improves the generation efficiency with the help of the masked language model of BERT (Kenton and Toutanova 2019) and ensures the correctness and continuity of syntax and semantics; sentence-level perturbation treats the whole sentence as the object of perturbation and usually realizes the attack by using rephrasing, re-decoding after encoding, and adding irrelevant sentences, and its perturbation. The result often leads to a large gap between the adversarial samples and the original input, which makes it difficult to ensure the quality of the adversarial samples and their validity. In this study, the StressTest (Naik et al. 2018) and CheckList (Bhatt et al. 2021) algorithms integrated into the attack framework realize the adversarial attack by adding irrelevant content at the end of the prompt data. A transfer-based adversarial attack occurs when the attacker generates adversarial samples by using the known model; these samples can mislead the model to make wrong judgments under the condition that the human eye is difficult to detect. The attacker then applies these adversarial samples to other models with different structures and parameters. To attack unknown models, the target model and the substitute model usually have similar model architectures (Li et al. 2024). This attack method shows the transferability of adversarial examples between different models, which seriously threatens to the security and robustness of machine learning models.
LLMs
LLMs have made remarkable progress and breakthroughs in recent years, and their capabilities have far exceeded those of traditional natural language processing (NLP) models. These models are trained by deep learning and large amounts of data to understand and generate natural language and perform various linguistic tasks such as text categorization, machine translation, Q&A, and text generation. Currently, LLMs represented by the GPT series (Brown et al. 2020; Radford et al. 2019; Ouyang et al. 2022; Achiam et al. 2023), ERNIE Bot (Sun
et al. 2020), Flan-T5 series (Raffel et al. 2020; Chung et al. 2024), LLaMA (Touvron et al. 2023), GLM (Zeng et al. 2022), and UL2 (Tay et al. 2022) have been released globally. With the enrichment of LLMs corpora and the increase in parameter levels, LLMs have given rise to security risks such as value alignment (Porsdam Mann et al. 2023), model misuse (Picazo-Sanchez and OrtizMartin 2024),hallucination (Lin et al. 2022), prompt injection (Strobelt et al. 2022), and so on. In addition, as a deep learning model, LLMs are vulnerable to traditional attacks, such as adversarial attacks, data poisoning, and backdoor attacks. Researchers have experimentally demonstrated that LLMs are robust to adversarial attacks but are still affected by them, and that there is a certain degree of transferability of adversarial samples between LLMs (Wang et al. 2023); Shi et al. influenced the output of LLMs by using a backdoor attack to manipulate the reward model in the fine-tuning phase of RL (Shi et al. 2023). Unlike traditional NLP models, LLMs are accessed mainly through human-computer interaction through prompts. The elements of Prompt mainly include Instruction, Context, Input Data and Output Indicator. Instruction, as a necessary element, defines the task to be performed. The context is an optional element that provides information about the context or environment of the task; the input data is an optional element that provides data to be processed or analyzed; and the output indicator is another optional element that specifies the type or format of output. CoT as emergent capability specific to LLMs, on the other hand, are stimulated by adding specific triggers or a step-by-step reasoning process to the prompt to stimulate the emergent capability of LLMs (Zoph et al. 2022); studies show that the larger the parameter level is, the more obvious the advantage of this capability is Wei et al. (2022). CoT is characterized by the transfer thinking of the same type of problems, which is usually used in combination with few-shot and zero-shot with ICL (Brown et al. 2020) to improve the model’s inference performance. In existing research, Complexity-based prompting (Fu et al. 2022) enhances multi-step reasoning by using complex examples, which leads to improved accuracy for LLMs on complex tasks. Automatic CoT prompting (of Thought Prompting in Large Language Models 2023) reduces manual work through automation and adapts to various tasks, but the quality of the generated chains can be inconsistent. Synthetic prompting (Shao et al. 2023) enriches prompts by generating reasoning demonstrations and improving performance on complex tasks, but it relies on the quality of pre-training data, which may not fully align with task requirements. This paper adopts a semi-automated approach to construct the CoT by selecting samples from the same dataset and


