The proposed attack
In this section, we introduce our proposed adversarial attack against LLMs. We begin by introducing our threat model and providing an overview of the attack framework. Then, we describe the various modules in detail.
Threat models
In this paper, we assume that attackers operate under black-box conditions, where they only have access to the model’s API and lack knowledge about its internal structure, parameters, or training process. Attackers first use a Transformer-based pre-trained model, fine-tuned for specific tasks, as a surrogate model. They apply existing adversarial attack algorithms to generate perturbationcapable samples. Then, we integrate the OpenAttack and PromptBench frameworks, utilizing CoT techniques and perturbation-capable adversarial samples. By employing various prompt engineering methods and perturbation strategies, we construct a CoT-based adversarial transfer attack framework to generate adversarial prompts. These adversarial prompts are stealthy,and when used to attack LLMs, they will cause the LLMs to produce wrong the output.
CTTA framework
This framework implements textual adversarial attacks at word, character, and sentence levels through the
OpenAttack attack framework and modifies the OpenAttack framework to obtain samples with perturbation capability. In addition, the CheckList and StressTest adversarial attack algorithms are extended in the OpenAttack attack framework based on the TextAttack (Morris et al. 2020) attack framework. Then, using the original data and the LLMs text generation interface, the task instructions are designed to generate the reasoning process for the initial task, which is the CoT of the LLMs on the realization of the initial task. Moreover, the transfer of adversarial samples on the CoT is realized by combining their specific task instructions according to different tasks. Finally, a black-box transfer-based attack is realized by using the LLM API interface. The overall framework is shown in Fig. 1.
Adversarial attack module
This module mainly realizes textual adversarial attacks at different perturbation levels through the OpenAttack attack framework, to obtain adversarial samples with perturbation capability. OpenAttack is the first textual adversarial attack toolkit to support all attack types, covering all perturbation granularities and victim model Accessibility. Fully compatible with the Huggingface community’s Transformer and Dataset libraries, supporting multi-language and multi-process attacks, and with high scalability and comprehensive review metrics, it is designed to assist researchers in rapid research and development related to textual adversarial attacks (Zeng et al. 2021). As shown in Table 1,the attack algorithms used in this module mainly includecharacter-level attacks: TextBugger, DeepWordBug; word-level attacks: BertAttack, TextFooler; and sentence-level attacks: CheckList, StressTest, the data are derived from the SST2 dataset, “1” is positive, “0” is negative. The framework diagram of the module is shown in Fig. 2, the module’s substitution models are fine-tuned language models on the input datasets, such as Bert, Roberta, etc. Different perturbation levels attacks satisfy the limits of the perturbation constraints during the attack, which have some differences depending on the algorithms, including semantic similarity, perturbation rate, word vector distance, cosine similarity, edit distance, and many other metrics, is used in the attack algorithm to evaluate, and adjust the generated adversarial samples. The module ultimately outputs adversarial samples that can spoof the substitution model, i.e., obtaining samples with perturbation capability.As shown in Eq. (1), the module utilizes the adversarial attack algorithm L, attacks the substitute model s,and finds the worst perturbation δ,the addition of perturbation to the clean sample x, so that the addition of perturbation to the clean sample x, leads to an incorrect output from the substitute model.


