Transfer‐based attack module
The main function of this module is to implement transfer adversarial attacks against LLMs, by utilizing the adversarial prompts constructed in the module to trick the LLMs into obtaining erroneous outputs. The attack diagram for this module is shown in Fig. 4. The module has both few-shot and zero-shot adversarial prompt samples, mainly through the API interface of LLMs for black-box attacks. If the model produces a different output from the clean sample, the attack is successful and results in an accuracy and performance drop of the model (Zhu et al. 2024). Among them, the final adversarial samples constructed in this paper are mainly perturbed against the input data portion of the prompt. The difference is that the PromptBench benchmark evaluation framework mainly perturbs the task instruction part of the prompt. Since optimal task instructions and CoT triggers are used in Module 2, model performance and accuracy are maximized on clean samples.Therefore, the objective of this module, as shown in Eq. (5), is to utilize the most effective adversarial attack, A, from module b to induce erroneous outputs from the target large model.
