Analysis and discussions
Experimental results demonstrate that the CTTAPrompt leads to a decline in performance and accuracy in the Flan-T5-large and UL2 LLMs across various perturbation granularities, outperforming existing adversarial prompt techniques. Notably, while the Vicuna model experiences some reduction in accuracy and performance under the CTTA-Prompt attack, the effect is not as pronounced as that observed in Flan-T5-large and UL2. To analyze this phenomenon, we calculated the initial performance of the models and the attack advantage of CTTA on these models, as illustrated in Fig. 9, the initial performance is positively correlated with the attack advantage. As noted in existing research (He et al. 2021) models with higher capability are more vulnerable to adversarial transfer attacks, whereas models with lower initial performance are less affected. As shown in Fig. 10a, the initial performance of the Vicuna model is significantly lower than that of Flan-T5-large and UL2, which explains the lower APDR and ACDC metrics for Vicuna, aligning with existing research findings. Additionally, as depicted in Fig. 10b,the adversarial robustness of vicuna against CTTA-Prompt is lower compared to guessing (Wang et al. 2023) results, indicating that our attack remains effective on the Vicuna model. Therefore, our attack method is valid and feasible, with models exhibiting better initial performance being more susceptible to the attack.The injection of chain-of-thought reasoning leads to a further decrease in the adversarial robustness of LLMs, increasing their vulnerability to adversarial attacks. This is especially evident in advanced models with high robustness, such as ChatGPT, where adversarial robustness on specific tasks decreases significantly. This also indicates that while LLMs continue to improve their performance, they may become
more sensitive to perturbations. Moreover, the activation of chain-of-thought capability further exposes this vulnerability.
Sample quality evaluation
Existing research points out that the definition of text perturbation d() must consider semantic similarity and syntactic fluency (Wang et al. 2022) to ensure the quality of adversarial samples. Therefore, this study uses the following evaluation indicators to evaluate the sample quality of CTTA-Prompt. Cosine Similarity (CosSim) is used to assess the semantic similarity between adversarial samples and clean samples, and the sentence fluency of Perplexity (PPL) measurement calculated by GPT-2 was used, Grammar Error Rate (GErr) is calculated using the grammar errors provided by the Language Tool. In this paper, 360 samples are randomly selected to calculate each measurement index for each LLM.The number of samples is equal to the number of prompt engineering times the number of perturbation algorithms times the number of randomly drawn samples times the number of cycles,that’s 2*6*10*3=360. As shown in Fig. 11a, the cosine similarity between the CTTA adversarial samples and the clean samples are all above 0.85, which is usually between 0.7 and 0.85 in the classical adversarial attack algorithm (Li et al. 2020; Zang et al. 2020; Garg and Ramakrishnan 2020). In advanced adversarial attack algorithms (Ni et al. 2024), this index typically fluctuates around 0.85. The AdvGLUE dataset used in the adversarial experiments of Bloom, GPTNeoX, and GPT-J LLMs is added with the constraint of similarity in the construction process to ensure the semantic similarity of the adversarial samples. Therefore, the adversarial examples constructed in this paper preserve the semantics of the clean examples. As shown in Fig. 11b, the PPL value of CTTA adversarial samples on zero-shot is between 120 and 180, and the PPL value on few-shot is between 20 and 40. Currently, the PPL value of the adversarial samples generated by the advanced adversarial attack algorithm is between 60 and 230 (Ni et al. 2024; Liu et al. 2022). The PPL value of the adversarial samples generated by the classical adversarial sample attack algorithm is between 90 and 350 (Li et al. 2020; Zang et al. 2020; Garg and Ramakrishnan 2020), which proves that the adversarial samples generated in this paper maintain the fluency of the sentences. As shown in Fig. 11c, the grammar error rate of the adversarial samples constructed in this paper is less than 0.12, the GErr value of the adversarial samples generated by the most advanced adversarial attack algorithm is between 0.10 and 0.20 (Ni et al. 2024), and the classical adversarial example attack algorithm is between 0.10 and 0.35 (Li et al. 2020; Zang et al. 2020; Garg and
